### Resolution by simplicial vector bundles

Let $X=\mathbb{P}^1_\mathbb{C}$ be the Riemann sphere $\mathbb{C}\cup\{\infty\}$ with the (Stein) cover $U_\alpha=X\setminus\{\infty\}$ and $U_\beta=X\setminus\{0\}$, and let $\mathcal{J}=\mathbb{I}(\{0\})$ be the sheaf of ideals corresponding to the subvariety $\{0\}\subset X$. Then $\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{O}_X/\mathcal{J}$ is a coherent sheaf.

The stalks of $\mathcal{S}$ are simple to understand: $\mathcal{S}_x=0$ for $x\neq0$, and $\mathcal{S}_0=\mathbb{C}$. Thus, over $U_\alpha$ we have the resolution
\begin{equation*}
    \xi_\alpha^\bullet =  \big(0\to\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_\alpha}\xrightarrow{f\mapsto z\cdot f}\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_\alpha}\big)\to \mathcal{S}\vert_{U_\alpha},
\end{equation*}
and over $U_\beta$ we have the resolution
\begin{equation*}
    \xi_\beta^\bullet = \big(0\to0\to0\big)\to \mathcal{S}\vert_{U_\beta}.
\end{equation*}

If we want to define a simplicial vector bundle then we are going to need a resolution of $\mathcal{S}_{\alpha\beta}=0$ by vector bundles over $U_{\alpha\beta}$, such that the simplicial conditions are satisfied. This gives us a problem however, since we have two different (but quasi-isomorphic, since $0,\infty\not\in U_{\alpha\beta}$, hence $(z\cdot)$ is an isomorphism) choices for such a complex:
\begin{align*}
\,^{(\alpha)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet &= \big(0\to\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\xrightarrow{f\mapsto z\cdot f}\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\big)\to \mathcal{S}\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}},\\
\,^{(\beta)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet &= \big(0\to0\to0\big)\to \mathcal{S}\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}.
\end{align*}
But we see that we can easily add the elementary sequence $\,_{(\beta)}^{(\alpha)}\mathscr{E}^\bullet=(0\to\mathcal{O}_X\to\mathcal{O}_X\to0)$ to the latter to obtain something isomorphic (since $0,\infty\not\in U_{\alpha\beta}$, so $1/z$ and $z$ are well defined and holomorphic) to the former: 
\begin{array}{rll}
\,^{(\alpha)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet = \big(0\to&\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\xrightarrow{f\mapsto z\cdot f}&\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\big)\\
&{\tiny f\mapsto z\cdot f}\downarrow&{\tiny\id}\downarrow\\
\,^{(\beta)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet\oplus\,_{(\beta)}^{(\alpha)}\mathscr{E}^\bullet = \big(0\to&\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\xrightarrow{\quad\id}&\mathcal{O}_X\vert_{U_{\alpha\beta}}\big).
\end{array}
(See [Simplicial vector bundles and twisting cochains](quiver-note-url/8E4622E1-ECC1-43EE-91D8-76CDDFAB5B46) for how finding such elementary sequences can be solved by the construction of a twisting cochain.)
We denote this isomorphism by $A_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet\colon\,^{(\alpha)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet\xrightarrow{\sim}\,^{(\beta)}\xi_{\alpha\beta}^\bullet\oplus\,_{(\beta)}^{(\alpha)}\mathscr{E}^\bullet$, so that $A_{\alpha\beta}^0=\id$ and $A_{\alpha\beta}^1=z\cdot(-)$.

What is important is that we don't need this second complex to define the resolution by simplicial vector bundles, but instead to be able to pull back the local connection over $U_\beta$ to a connection over $U_{\alpha\beta}$ in a non-trivial manner.

At this point, the construction stabilises: we get two complexes over $U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}$, but they are identical ($0\to\mathcal{O}_X|_{U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}}\to\mathcal{O}_X|_{U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}}$). Further, since our cover consists of only two distinct opens sets, any $n$-intersection for $n\geqslant3$ will be trivially identical to some (possibly trivial) $2$-intersection (either $U_{\alpha\alpha}$, $U_{\alpha\beta}$, or $U_{\beta\beta}$). Thus we have constructed a complex of simplicial vector bundles on the Čech nerve of $X$ that give a resolution of $\mathcal{S}$ (pulled back trivially to the Čech nerve):
\begin{equation*}
    0\to\mathcal{E}_\bullet^1\to\mathcal{E}_\bullet^0\to\mathcal{S}_\bullet
\end{equation*}
where $\mathcal{E}_\bullet^1=\mathcal{E}_\bullet^0$ is given by
\begin{align*}
    &\mathcal{E}_0^i\quad \text{on}\quad U_\alpha\sqcup U_\beta\quad\text{is}\quad\mathcal{O}_X|_{U_\alpha}\sqcup0\\
    &\mathcal{E}_1^i\quad \text{on}\qquad U_{\alpha\beta}\qquad\text{is}\qquad\mathcal{O}_X|_{U_{\alpha\beta}}
\end{align*}
and the map $\mathcal{E}_\bullet^1\to\mathcal{E}_\bullet^0$ is given by
\begin{align*}
    \mathcal{E}_0^1&\to\mathcal{E}_0^0\\
    \mathcal{O}_X|_{U_\alpha}&\overset{\cdot z}{\mapsto} \mathcal{O}_X|_{U_\alpha}\\
    0&{\mapsto} 0\\[1em]
    \mathcal{E}_1^1&\to\mathcal{E}_1^0\\
    \mathcal{O}_X|_{U_{\alpha\beta}}&\overset{\cdot z}{\mapsto} \mathcal{O}_X|_{U_{\alpha\beta}}.
\end{align*}

### Simplicial connections and the first Chern class

On each $p$-intersection $U_{\alpha_0\ldots\alpha_p}$ we get $p+1$ connections on $\mathcal{E}_p^i$, coming from the $U_{\alpha_0},\ldots,U_{\alpha_p}$ (all pulled back to $U_{\alpha_0}$). Generally, given an isomorphism of vector bundles $\varphi\colon E\xrightarrow{\sim}F$ with a connection $\nabla_F$ on $F$, the pullback bundle $\varphi^*\nabla_F$ on $E$ is given by $(\varphi^{-1}\otimes\varphi^*)\circ\nabla_F\circ\varphi$. Locally, this takes the trivial connection $\mathrm{d}$ on $F$ to $\mathrm{d}+\varphi^{-1}\mathrm{d}\varphi$ on $E$.

simplicial vector bundle|$p$|$p$-intersection|local connections
-|-|-|-
$\mathcal{E}^0_\bullet$|0|$U_\alpha$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial)
-|-|$U_\beta$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial)
-|1|$U_{\alpha\beta}$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial, from $U_\alpha$) and $\mathrm{d}+(A_{\alpha\beta}^0)^{-1}\mathrm{d}A_{\alpha\beta}^0=\mathrm{d}$ (trivial, from $U_\beta$)
$\mathcal{E}^1_\bullet$|0|$U_\alpha$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial)
-|-|$U_\beta$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial)
-|1|$U_{\alpha\beta}$|$\mathrm{d}$ (trivial, from $U_\alpha$) and $\mathrm{d}+(A_{\alpha\beta}^1)^{-1}\mathrm{d}A_{\alpha\beta}^1=\mathrm{d}+\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}$ (from $U_\beta$)

Now we can form the barycentric connections $\nabla_\bullet^i$ on the $\mathcal{E}_\bullet^i$, where $\nabla_0^i=\mathrm{d}$, and
\begin{align*}
    \nabla_1^0 &= t_0\mathrm{d}+t_1\mathrm{d} = \mathrm{d}\\
    \nabla_1^1 &= t_0\mathrm{d}+t_1\left(\mathrm{d}+\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}\right) = \mathrm{d} + t_1\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}.
\end{align*}

Looking only at the $p=1$ level (i.e. over $U_{\alpha\beta}$, which in this example is the only non-trivial bit), we calculate the curvature of these two simplicial connections:
\begin{align*}
    K(\nabla_1^0) &= 0\\
    K(\nabla_1^1) &= \mathrm{d}\left(t_1\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}\right)+\left(t_1\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}\right)^2\\
    &= \mathrm{d}t_1\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}+t_1^2\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}\right)^2.
\end{align*}

Then fibre integration of the $(1,1)$-terms (i.e. $\Omega_{U_{\alpha\beta}}^1\otimes\Omega_{\Delta^1}^1$) gives us the individual first Atiyah classes (i.e. the first exponential Chern classes):
\begin{align*}
    \mathrm{at}_{\mathcal{E}_\bullet^0} &= \int_{\Delta^\bullet}K\left(\nabla_\bullet^0\right) = 0\\
    \mathrm{at}_{\mathcal{E}_\bullet^1} &= \int_{\Delta^\bullet}K\left(\nabla_\bullet^1\right) = \int_{\Delta^1}\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}\mathrm{d}t_1 = \frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}.
\end{align*}

Then the total Atiyah classes (i.e. the Chern characters) are given by
\begin{align*}
    \mathrm{at}^\text{tot}\left(\mathcal{E}_\bullet^0\right) &= 1\\
    \mathrm{at}^\text{tot}\left(\mathcal{E}_\bullet^1\right) &= 1+\frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}.
\end{align*}

Finally, we use the fact that, for a resolution $\mathcal{R}^\bullet=(\ldots\to\mathcal{R}_\bullet^2\to\mathcal{R}_\bullet^1)$ of a simplicial sheaf $\mathcal{R_\bullet^0}$, the Chern character of $\mathcal{R}_\bullet^0$ is given by the alternating sum of the Chern characters of the $\mathcal{R}_\bullet^i$ (this is just from $K$-theory and the Whitney sum formula), to see that
\begin{equation*}
    \mathrm{ch}\left(\mathcal{S}\right) = \mathrm{at}^\text{tot}\left(\mathcal{S}_\bullet\right) = \frac{\mathrm{d}z}{z}
\end{equation*}
where the first equality is discussed in our construction of the simplicial Atiyah classes (also, see [Chern classes, exponential Chern classes, the Chern character, and Atiyah classes](quiver-note-url/2F9529E0-462E-4649-959A-0C69AF00E69C)).
